<li id="cite_note-29"><b><a href="#cite_ref-29" title="">^</a></b> Examples: (T1) <i>Mha.mha</i> (<span lang="zh-cmn-Hans" xml:lang="zh-cmn-Hans">妈妈</span> <i>Māma</i>), "Mum"; (T2) <i>mamuh</i> (<span lang="zh-cmn-Hani" xml:lang="zh-cmn-Hani">麻木</span> <i>mámù</i>), "numb".</li>
<li id="cite_note-30"><b><a href="#cite_ref-30" title="">^</a></b> Chao calls the character the "sociological word", since it is the unit by which children's vocabulary is measured, journalists are paid and telegrams charged for. Chao(1968a): 136.</li>
<li id="cite_note-31"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31" title="">^</a></b> For thorough discussions, see Chao(1968a): 138–143 and Kratochvíl(1968):89–99.</li>
<li id="cite_note-32"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32" title="">^</a></b> DeFrancis(1950): Ch 4, note 46.</li>
<li id="cite_note-33"><b><a href="#cite_ref-33" title="">^</a></b> See also the <a href="/wiki/Spelling_in_Gwoyeu_Romatzyh#Pinyin_comparison:_all_tones" title="Spelling in Gwoyeu Romatzyh">table of Chinese provinces</a> in the main article, comparing GR and Pinyin spellings.</li>
